TopicTitle: KSP Interstellar Extended Continued Development Thread

Articles.Content: Excuse me, I would like to know if the CKAN entry could be changed to not have the Community Tech Tree as a dependency and instead as recommended, I ask this because I'm trying to use the Engineering Tech Tree instead, which already has support for this mod.

Excuse me, I would like to know if the CKAN entry could be changed to not have the Community Tech Tree as a dependency and instead as recommended, I ask this because I'm trying to use the Engineering Tech Tree instead, which already has support for this mod.

 

sounds fair, I will look if it is feasible
Oh dear, I'm getting a download error for this mod, error 404, I think the link on KCAN might be broken, just wanted to let you know, going to go manually install it.

On 2/21/2017 at 1:15 AM, FreeThinker said:

Well that certainly not intended, you should be able to start in any mode, it's just that the lighter atoms generate more charged particles, I need to verify ..

Indeed that is the QSR main intended purpose. You are right about the antimatter endurance problem, antimatter at first sight looks very promising for warp travel or charged particle propulsion, until you realize you need tons of it and the storage isn't exactly efficient. Antimatter shines best for short duration power surges, not longer than a few days, but if you need high amount of power for months that you are better of with Advanced Fusion or QSR

These things generate a ton of heat... I have a ship with a 7.5m warp drive which seems to need 2 QSRs to power it.. even with 4 umbrella radiators scaled to 3.75m I can't keep the wasteheat generation under control.  I need to figure out a new way to cool these things.  Unfortunately the size and shape of the reactors gives me a large amount of my craft's surface area to which radiators cannot be attached

Notice the EM drive produces extreme amount of a lot of waste heat (99% of energy is turned into waste heat) and therefore its power is very limited (compared with other electric engines). As a consequence it's thrust is very limited. But it main asset is not thrust but very high isp , which is hard to calculate but depends on the methods of power production. With Fusion is about  100.000.000 s And you can use it during time acceleration, Use it preferably in combination with persistent rotation o spiral out of of low orbit.

So I'm trying to set up an IR power network around kerbin, and I'm having some issues.

I've got a sea-based 3.75m laser putting out a 9GW signal, which should have a spot size of <10m out to about 3 million km.  That part works fine - things directly receiving power from the station behave as expected.  The problem arises when I try to use pivoted IR mirror relays.  I've tried various setups, but I currently have 4 mirrors evenly spaced around kerbin at about 500km, and I'm having two major problems:

1. The spot sizes don't make any sense.  All the mirror rockets have mk1 receivers on them, so I can see what kind of power they're actually receiving.  Again, the relay directly above the power station works fine, and shows a spot size of 1-2m, and the expected 9(ish) GJ of thermal power.  But when I jump over to one of the adjacent relays, which should have a total travel distance of less than a million km, the first spot size listed (I assume that's the active one) is 40+ meters, and the received power is only about 200 MJ (as I'd expect, given that spot size).

2.  If I jump over to the relay on the far side of the planet (so two relays away from the ground station), the first spot size has increased a bit more to about 50m, and the receiver says its not even connected to the network (and, indeed, receives no power).

 

Soooo... is this a bug?  Or is there something about mirror relays I'm not understanding?
